"Jerome McGann, among others, observes the way in which a lexicon of eighteenth-century ideas — ancient ideas if we consider their provenance in romanticism’s fascination with the pre-modern — have been conserved across time and in a language we take for our own contemporary literary-critical discourse. As McGann points out, romanticism’s pre-eminence as a structure of critical consciousness or cultural metaphor is the result of the ‘process of reification’ the ‘ideology of romanticism’ has undergone — a process underwritten by the academy. As McGann puts it ‘[t]oday the scholarship and interpretation of Romantic works is dominated by an uncritical absorption in Romanticism’s own self-representations’, The Romantic Ideology: A Critical Investigation, (Chicago and London: University of Chicago Press, 1983), p.137. For a sense of the persistence of romanticism in contemporary debates about literature and critical theory see Justin Clemens’s chapter ‘The Institution of Romanticism’ in The Romanticism of Contemporary Theory: Institution, Aesthetics, Nihilism (Aldershot: Ashgate, 2003).",
